Pod security admission, et-see-dee encryption, and image security.

First, pod security admission. Setting a security context on each pod is great, but you also want a blanket policy that rejects pods which do not meet the bar. Pod security admission does that. It replaced the removed pod security policy.

It defines three levels. Privileged, which allows anything. Baseline, with sane defaults, no privileged, no host paths, no host namespaces. And restricted, the hardest line, requiring non root, dropping all capabilities, and using seccomp. You apply a level per namespace, by label, in one of three modes. Enforce, which rejects the pod. Audit, which allows but logs. And warn, which allows but returns a warning. The migration recipe is, start with warn and audit at the target level, fix the pods, then switch to enforce. For finer rules, use gatekeeper, with rego, or kyverno, with yaml, both beyond the see-kay-ay.

Second, et-see-dee encryption at rest. By default, secret data in et-see-dee is base sixty-four, not encrypted. So anyone with read access to the data directory, or an old backup, reads every secret. The fix is an encryption configuration, read by the ay-pee-eye server via a flag, which encrypts secrets, and optionally config maps, before writing them, using an ay-ee-ess or a k-m-s provider. The first provider encrypts, and all providers can decrypt. So to rotate, add the new key first, re-encrypt all secrets, then drop the old key. Keep the identity provider last during migration. And note, this protects data at rest only. Not in transit, which tee-el-ess already handles, and not inside the pod.

And third, image security. Pin digests, not moving tags. Use image pull secrets for private registries, from notebook five. Sign images with cosign and sigstore, and verify at admission with kyverno. Scan in continuous integration, with trivy. And detect at runtime with falco. On our map, this is the pod security admission chip in the security box. The namespace wide enforcement, over everything module ten hardens.
